WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:07.000
So what we're going to talk about today is a new way to use Shiny that we at RStudio have called Shiny Gadgets.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:15.000
And Shiny Gadgets are a tool that you as an R developer can use yourself or give to other R developers.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:21.000
They're a way to apply the interactivity that Shiny provides to a new set of users, people who program in R.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
And to begin this, let's talk about what a gadget is in contrast to what a Shiny app is.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.000
I noticed from the poll that about a third of the people here haven't used Shiny,

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:35.000
so I'm actually going to spend a little more time talking about Shiny than I thought I would.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:40.000
And that's the sort of great feedback that I'm glad the polls can provide for us.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
If you've used Shiny, or if you haven't used Shiny before,

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Shiny is an R package that allows you to create web apps with R.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And the use case for Shiny would be that you have some sort of data or simulation or model that you want to fit using R.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.000
R is really good for that.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:02.000
But you want to make it available to people who, A, might not have R, might not know how to code in R,

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
and might just want to get to it easily and do the things they could do,

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:11.000
like type on a keyboard or click their mouse, to control what happens in the app.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:14.000
And that's what Shiny does. It builds a web app from R.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.000
Your users get to visit that app over a network.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:21.000
The web app is essentially a web page, so any network that can serve up a web page,

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:24.000
you can put the app on and viewers can look at it.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.000
You can also keep your web apps local and just look at them on your own computer.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:33.000
But the idea behind Shiny is you're packaging your results in a way that someone who doesn't know R

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
can access easily and use easily.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:41.000
And if you are completely unfamiliar with Shiny, which I doubt is the case,

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.000
but if you've never even heard of Shiny before, you could go to the RStudio.com website.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:50.000
We have a showcase of Shiny apps there that you could play with and get a sense of what Shiny does.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:54.000
So that was the motive for creating the Shiny package.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.000
It's a very, very popular package.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:02.000
What we're going to talk about today is a way to use this package and do something a little different.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Instead of creating a web app that you then serve over a network to people who don't have R

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:12.000
and aren't interested in using R, you can use Shiny to create an interactive tool

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:18.000
that is loaded locally in an R user's R session that they can use to do interactive things.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:23.000
We're calling these tools that stay in your R session Shiny Gadgets.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:31.000
And I have prepared a demo of a Shiny Gadget to make it clear what we're talking about.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.000
So this is my RStudio session.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:38.000
You see I have some scripts loaded up here and there's some files in my directory.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.000
These are the files that I'll be putting on GitHub after the webinar.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:44.000
And the first file here is called GetPassword.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:50.000
It loads a couple of libraries, loads a couple of packages, including the Shiny package,

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:52.000
and then defines a function called GetPassword.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
If I were to source this, that function would be defined.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:59.000
You can see over here in my environment it now exists, GetPassword.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:02.000
And if I wanted to run that function, I could do so.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:08.000
And this function is unique because what it does when you run it is it calls a Shiny app

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:10.000
or what I'm going to call a Shiny Gadget.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.000
So here I'm running the function.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:13.000
It opens this window.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:16.000
This window is a Shiny app or a Shiny Gadget.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:19.000
It has a field here that I could type in.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:21.000
It has some buttons that I can click.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.000
And this is right here in my local RStudio session.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:29.000
The idea behind this particular gadget is I could type in a password here.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:34.000
So let me type in a password.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:35.000
You can't see it.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:36.000
It's a password field.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:41.000
But then when I'm done using this gadget, I can click the Done button,

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:47.000
and the gadget will return what I've typed to my RStudio session or my R session.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
So I click Done, and then we see down here at the command line,

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.000
this is the password I typed in, hello world.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:57.000
And it's returned right to the R environment that I called GetPassword from.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Now in this case it's called GetPassword from the top level,

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.000
but in R you can call a function from another function.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
You can save the results to a variable and so on.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:11.000
So I can use GetPassword inside other R code.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.000
When that code gets to GetPassword, it will launch the Shiny Gadget.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.000
The user can type in their password with the gadget.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.000
I can arrange to have that saved and then used by the function I called GetPassword,

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:25.000
perhaps to log into a database or whatnot.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:30.000
What I would have achieved is an interactive way for my users to type in passwords

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.000
required by the code that they're running.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Not just that, this format of typing in passwords here has some advantages

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:42.000
because the actual password to connect to the database or do whatever I'm going to do with that password

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:45.000
doesn't need to be hard-coded into my code.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.000
So I can show this code on GitHub and not worry about security issues.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:53.000
When the code's run, that's when the password will be typed in and so on.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:58.000
But the gadget aspect of this is it is a function that calls a Shiny app locally,

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:04.000
and then once your user uses a Shiny app, the Shiny app passes values back to the function that called it,

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:09.000
or the R environment that called it, that your code can then go on and use.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:14.000
So if we compare that to Shiny apps as you may have used them in the past,

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:19.000
you can see a gadget is used more in line with other types of programming.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
It's part of the programming process for the user,

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:26.000
where Shiny apps are used normally to communicate results or to make simulations

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:30.000
or models accessible to a wider audience.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:35.000
Gadgets are run in your local R session to go pass results back into that R session,

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:39.000
where Shiny apps are designed to be self-contained and to run on a network later

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:43.000
when you, the R developer, aren't keeping an eye on things.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:47.000
And then Shiny gadgets are invoked from functions.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:51.000
They're always called by an R function and then they appear,

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.000
whereas Shiny apps are deployed on a server and they sort of wait there on the server

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:59.000
until someone visits a web address, and then the server loads up the app

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:03.000
and the person gets to see it when they want to see.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:07.000
So if you were to think of the main difference between Shiny gadgets and Shiny apps,

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:10.000
Shiny gadgets are much more for the R developer,

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:13.000
where Shiny apps are much more for your audience.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:17.000
In fact, you could say that Shiny gadgets are for data scientists,

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:21.000
and Shiny apps are for, you know, we could be nice and call the people who use them decision makers,

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.000
but maybe they're just the people you want to communicate your results to.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:29.000
In other words, Shiny gadgets give you a chance to be like, you know,

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:31.000
in the 1980s we had this hair club for men.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:37.000
When you use a Shiny gadget, you're not just a Shiny developer, but you're also a Shiny client.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.000
The potential for this interface with Shiny is pretty large.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:46.000
You could just use your imagination to imagine things that you do with code

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:50.000
that actually isn't very easy to do in an iterative code fashion.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:54.000
But then if you made that interactive with a Shiny gadget,

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:58.000
you could do it much more quickly, or your users could do it more quickly.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.000
So think of things like cleaning data and checking for outliers,

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.000
or filtering data, or just picking nice colors for your graphs.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.000
They're a little hard to do at the command line,

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:11.000
but you could do easily with a Shiny gadget.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:16.000
And by putting that gadget into your code, you make that more a part of your reproducible workflow,

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:21.000
even though it is something that you're kind of doing spontaneously on the fly.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:26.000
So the gadget that I showed you guys is called Get Password.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:31.000
It looks sort of like this, and I'm going to use it as a quick run-through

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:34.000
of what you need to know to make your own Shiny gadgets.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:37.000
There are three essential features for every gadget.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
We'll look at them quickly with Get Password, and then I'll show you a more complex gadget

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:44.000
that will allow us to go into the details.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:51.000
But the way to think of these features is gadgets are used in the context of a programming workflow.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:56.000
If you want to interrupt that workflow and get into a gadget,

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
then come back into that workflow with the results of the gadget,

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.000
you're going to first need to create a way to access the gadget.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:05.000
And that's going to be by writing a function that calls the gadget.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:08.000
So here for Get Password, that function is Get Password.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
That's pretty simple to do. I'll show you how to do it, but it's just writing a function.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:17.000
Next, you need to actually create the gadget experience that your user gets.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.000
This is similar to any Shiny app where you lay out a UI,

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:23.000
but we've created a new package that can help you make gadgets specifically

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
because gadgets are a little different than other Shiny apps,

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
and I'll show you what that means in a second.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
And finally, after your user has used the gadget,

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
you'll want to have a way to take what they have input into the gadget

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:41.000
and put it back into your programming workflow where it can then be used by other functions.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:46.000
And you'll do that with a function called StopApp, and we'll look at that as well.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:51.000
If we were to scan quickly the code for Get Password, you could see all these things showing up there.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:55.000
Get Password is a function. I saved it as a function, I defined it as a function,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:59.000
and I invoked it by calling the function.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:05.000
The UI of this Shiny app is made with these new functions that you might not recognize

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:09.000
if you're a Shiny developer because they come from the mini UI package.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:15.000
And then I'm using a special function called StopApp to handle what I want the app to do

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
when the user closes the app.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.000
And this is the step where the input that's been given to the app

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:24.000
will get passed back to the code that called the app.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:31.000
So to illustrate these things, and to illustrate some of the options and flexibility you have around them,

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:35.000
I have a more sophisticated app, which I will save in the GitHub repository

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:38.000
in the R script brush underscore gadget dot R.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:42.000
And I have it open in my RStudio session right here.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:47.000
Here's the code that makes the app. Let's first try out the app to see what it does.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:53.000
So I'm running PickPoints, which is the function that saved the gadget.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.000
It opened over here my viewer window.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:01.000
And what you can see is this is a scatter plot of the empty cards dataset

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:05.000
with the weight variable on the x-axis, the mpg variable on the y-axis.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.000
And that comes from the way I called PickPoints.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:12.000
I said, you know, here's my dataset, here's the x-axis, here's the y-axis variables.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:17.000
And the reason this syntax follows is because of how I wrote this function.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.000
Now that I have the scatter plot of points here,

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:25.000
I could use the gadget to select actual data points in the data

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:30.000
by highlighting them with some brushing, using Shiny's interactive graphics brushing capability.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
Then I could tell the gadget with these buttons down here,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:36.000
throw out these points, I don't really want to use them,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
then they become a light gray.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:41.000
Maybe I could throw out some more points.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:44.000
Maybe I decide I actually do want to use these two points,

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
so I say, you know, put those points back into play.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:51.000
Or I could, using this gadget, make all the points disappear

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:54.000
so I can just select the ones I want one at a time.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.000
Or if I've gotten too far and messed up, I'll just reset it all and start again.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:03.000
What happens when you click done for this gadget

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:09.000
is all the points that are still highlighted will be selected.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
Well, to be completely accurate,

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
the gadget's going to return a vector of true and falses

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
that can be added to our dataset of two cars.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
Every point that's highlighted here in the gadget,

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:22.000
every point that I've selected, will have a true,

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
and every point that I haven't selected will have a false.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:27.000
So when I click done, we can see I get this vector back.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:32.000
And if I wanted to be more, you know, maybe to drive a point home,

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.000
if I wanted to use this later, I would save it to something.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:38.000
So now I'm going to invoke the gadget again.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
I'll select a few points again, click done.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.000
Now this time, I've saved the results.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.000
You can see selected appears up here in my environment.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.000
And I can use this in code.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:54.000
If I wanted to get those actual points, I could subset empty cars with selected.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.000
Those are the points that I ended up highlighting in that gadget.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:00.000
So you can see what this gadget does,

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:04.000
and hopefully you can see, you know, this might actually be a useful task.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
So let's use the code in the gadget

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.000
to get a better sense of how we made the gadget.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.000
And we're going to have to think about those three steps,

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
how to call or invoke the gadget from our programming workflow,

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:18.000
what user experience the user has inside the gadget,

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
and then how to return results back to the programming workflow.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.000
The way that we call a gadget, as I said earlier,

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.000
was we would save it as a function.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
So here I'm creating a function called pick points.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:34.000
I'm literally just using R's function to do this.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
And down here, you know, I'm closing the function.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
Since I'm writing a function,

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.000
I could set any arguments that I want for the function.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.000
So here I chose three arguments, data, x, and y.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:51.000
And wherever these arguments or symbols appear in the body of the function,

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:56.000
R will substitute in whatever the user passes as data for data in that place.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:57.000
So here I have data.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:00.000
This will be the data set the user selects.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.000
The past example is empty cars.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.000
And same for x and y.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:07.000
Now what's inside that function is important.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:11.000
First I'm creating a UI object and then a server object.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
If you're new to Shiny,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:17.000
you should know that these are the two objects that you have to create to create a Shiny app.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:20.000
If you've already created Shiny apps, then you recognize what I'm doing here

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.000
is I'm creating the UI for a Shiny app and the server logic for a Shiny app.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:28.000
For a regular Shiny app, you would create these things and save them,

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:33.000
and then you'd call runApp or a similar function to load that app.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:36.000
What we're doing here is we're creating the objects,

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:42.000
and then we're calling runGadget as the last line of the function with those objects UI and server.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:46.000
What runGadget does is it launches the gadget,

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
and it's the last line of the function.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
So the gadget is what's returned from the function,

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:57.000
and what this gadget itself is going to return is the values that we tell it to return when someone clicks Done.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:02.000
In terms of setting up your gadget,

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
it's just like setting up a Shiny app with UI and server,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
and then use runGadget instead of runApp to launch it.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:14.000
That's how we could invoke the gadget from the programming workflow.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
Now let's look a little at the user experience for this gadget.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:23.000
You could see that I'm loading the package MiniUI here for this gadget.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:27.000
The UI functions in the gadget come from MiniUI.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:30.000
If we look at the MiniUI package,

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:36.000
you can see it's actually a fairly small package.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:40.000
We developed this to work alongside Shiny for making Shiny gadgets,

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:46.000
and it has a few different pieces of Shiny layout that you can use.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:52.000
The reason we thought it would be important to develop a new package for gadget layout versus a Shiny app layout

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:55.000
is that most gadgets tend to be very small.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:00.000
The space that you use on the screen when you make your gadget

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:03.000
is normally limited to either your RStudio viewer pane,

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.000
or you might have a pop-up window or something.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:16.000
If you picture the dashboard over here on the left,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
we fit all sorts of stuff in there.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:22.000
We conceivably have our user's whole computer screen to work with,

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
but then if you look at the gadget,

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
which tries to fit the same elements into the space that a gadget would appear in,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.000
it's too jumbled. There's too much going on in there.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:35.000
Also, there's elements of Shiny layout that try to resize things automatically

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:40.000
and create a fluid layout that don't really apply to Shiny gadgets.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:45.000
MiniUI provides a way to fit elements concisely into a small space,

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:49.000
utilizing all the space available at the same time as possible,

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
so everything fits into your gadget.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:58.000
The main function for the MiniUI package is MiniPage.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
It takes the place of FluidPage,

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:05.000
and what it does is it arranges to have a Shiny gadget that fills up the whole space.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:10.000
There's some extra CSS involved in doing this,

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:15.000
and so the things that go into MiniPage need to expect the sort of CSS tweaking

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.000
that MiniPage is using to take advantage of that space,

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:24.000
which means you tend to only put into your MiniPage elements from the MiniUI package,

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
like MiniTabPanel, MiniTabStripPanel, and so on.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
However, you want to have plots in your gadget.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
You want to have things that you'd put in a normal Shiny app.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
These aren't things designed specifically to use MiniUI.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
MiniUI came about later.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:42.000
We do have MiniContentPanel,

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:47.000
which acts as a bridge between the things like a plot output that you'll show in your UI

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:52.000
and the special MiniUI that takes advantage of the space.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:57.000
Anything you put in MiniContentPanel will be fit into the space in an appropriate way,

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:00.000
and as your user resizes the space or whatnot, it'll work out well.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:03.000
Here I've put plot output inside MiniContentPanel.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:10.000
The other things in the UI that you'll want to know about are

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:14.000
almost every gadget has a gadget title bar at the top of the page.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.000
This is a very concise way to label the gadget.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:19.000
Here I'm calling it Shiny Gadget Example.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:23.000
It automatically inserts a Cancel button and a Done button.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:26.000
The Cancel button lets your user lock out of the gadget

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
should they not want to be there for some reason.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:32.000
It'll return, by default, an error, a user error.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:38.000
When someone cancels a gadget, the gadget doesn't really know what to return to the programming workload.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:43.000
You can intervene and override what happens when someone clicks the Cancel button if you want.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:46.000
The Done button saves. It's an action button.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
It saves its result as input dollar sign Done,

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:52.000
and it's up to you to decide what happens when someone clicks on Done.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
That'll be the next thing we talk about.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:58.000
We talked about MiniContentPanel.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:02.000
This is just how you put regular input into your MiniUI.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:11.000
But then some interesting things that you might use to create features in your app

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:13.000
are MiniButtonBlock.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:14.000
We've seen this with our app.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:19.000
What it does is it gives you a chance to add various buttons to the bottom of your block.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:20.000
These would be action buttons.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
You can control what they do.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:26.000
Alternatively, you could add a TabStripPanel.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.000
This is similar to a TabPanel in the Shiny app,

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:32.000
where each of the icons here at the bottom of the panel,

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:36.000
when clicked, opens up a new tab in the content of the panel.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:39.000
I have an app that demonstrates what this does.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.000
Go back to RStudio.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:45.000
The Tabs app uses a MiniTabStripPanel.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:51.000
To use MiniTabStripPanel, you have to create MiniTabPanels for each button in the app.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:54.000
Let me source this and then just run it.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:55.000
This app is all pure demo.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:59.000
It doesn't really have a logical function.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:04.000
When the Parameters button is clicked here, we have this slider in the app.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.000
We have our gadget title bar at the top.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
If we look at how we're calling MiniTabStripPanel,

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:15.000
the first TabPanel contains its own MiniContentPanel that has the slider that we see.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:17.000
It has its own name parameters.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:19.000
That name appears down here.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:26.000
Then I've used the icon feature with the icon function to add a sliders icon to appear above the parameters

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:28.000
to make this a little more visual.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:30.000
Since we're working in such a small space,

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:33.000
this is a great chance to take advantage of the phrase,

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
a picture is worth a thousand words.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:40.000
Whenever we can make things graphical here, it can convey a lot of information with a small amount of space.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
The next MiniTabPanel is called Visualize.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:43.000
We see it here.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.000
It has an area chart icon.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:51.000
The names of these icons, you might recognize, are coming from Font Awesome.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:55.000
If I click on Visualize, it opens a new tab in the center here.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:57.000
Now I have a graph.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:00.000
Map and Data do the same things.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.000
Data is actually an HTML widget that we put inside our app.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:09.000
There's some other layer of interactivity here in this app.

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:11.000
Map demonstrates a button block here.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:13.000
It has a button block with a single button.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:19.000
The way I did that is I added MiniButtonBlock into the TabPanel for the Map tab.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:21.000
First I have my content.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:22.000
Then I have my button block.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:23.000
I put an action button in there.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:25.000
It's called Reset.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:42.000
Before we move on, those are just a few building blocks to work with.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:46.000
But you can combine them to make sophisticated gadgets.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:50.000
There's really not so much more you'd want to do to a gadget, so this will take you quite far.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:56.000
If we go back to the Help menu, you can see that there's really not much else in this MiniUI package.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:03.000
The other functions here handle the actual bars that are added by default to your gadget title bar.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:08.000
If we stop that app, if we were to look at gadget title bar,

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:16.000
you can see that it does have some defaults that are using the tab completion.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:20.000
You can see it's calling these things by default, so you don't have to.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:23.000
But if you wanted to overwrite, for example, the word done in the done button,

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:28.000
then here for the right argument, you'd actually spell out the right argument and choose your own title.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:35.000
All of that's actually probably pretty familiar to you, especially if you're a shiny developer.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:40.000
I'm going to take it for granted that you've been writing our functions and that you've been creating UI and server,

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:42.000
because that's what you do as a shiny developer.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:46.000
But this step might be new to everybody involved.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:50.000
That's stopping an app and returning values back out of the app.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:55.000
You can do this with a regular shiny app, but it really becomes essential when you use a shiny gadget.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:57.000
It revolves around a function called stopApp.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:03.000
To take advantage of stopApp, you do need to know how to use observeEvent,

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:07.000
which is a shiny function for handling events.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:11.000
The way observeEvent works is you call this in the server logic of your function.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:16.000
Just like you'd make a reactive expression or set up an observer or a render statement,

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.000
you would set up an observeEvent block.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:22.000
There's two observeEvent blocks, one for each of the buttons here.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:28.000
What observeEvent does is it sets up an observer that watches a reactive input.

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:36.000
Every shiny gadget is going to save input$cancel and input$done as inputs for the two buttons in the title bar,

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:39.000
unless you intervene in naming something different.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:44.000
These two observeEvents are going to watch those buttons and wait to see when their values change.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:51.000
Action buttons have an arbitrary value that increments by one every time someone clicks the button.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:53.000
When someone clicks that button, that value will change.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:57.000
These observeEvent statements will notice that that has changed.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:05.000
The next part of the observeEvent call is a code recipe that observeEvent should run whenever the first value changes.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:11.000
Here, when input$done changes, observeEvent is going to run this code, stopApp.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:18.000
What stopApp does is, first, it exits the app. It closes the app.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:25.000
Then, second, it passes to the environment that called the app anything that you put as arguments for stopApp.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:28.000
If you put multiple things here, you could create a list for stopApp to return.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:34.000
Here, let's assume that this app created vowels$keep.

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:37.000
Perhaps that's a reactive expression. Perhaps it's a static value.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:41.000
stopApp is going to return a non-reactive copy of it.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:48.000
It will be the current value of vowels$keep when the app is closed, when the user clicks done.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:54.000
This is the trick for delivering values collected by your app to the code that called the app.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:57.000
If that code stored those values into an object, they'd immediately be stored there.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:01.000
You could proceed as a regular R developer using that object.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:13.000
If we look here in our Brush Gadget app, you can see that I have set up down here some observeEvent statements.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:16.000
These observeEvent statements are calling stopApp.

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:20.000
When someone clicks done, it's actually going to stop the app and return vowels$keep,

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:28.000
which is something I set up to be that list of trues and falses that express which values have been selected.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:35.000
If someone calls in and puts vowels$cancel, then I've arranged for this app to just stop and return null instead of returning an error.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:42.000
I want to take you into an application of Shiny Gadgets.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:48.000
I'll get to that in a moment, but there's one last thing that I realize now I've brushed over that I would like to draw your attention to.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:50.000
I think Shiny Gadgets are pretty simple.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:53.000
We've had half an hour, and we've covered almost everything that are in them.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:55.000
This is just the last topic.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:58.000
You may have noticed, for example, when I run this app,

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:07.000
it appears down here in the viewer pane.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.000
I'll pop that out.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:20.000
But when I ran the getPassword app, it appeared in a dialog box.

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:24.000
It sort of floated above the screen right there.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:28.000
You can also arrange for your gadget to appear in your user's browser.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:31.000
The way you do that is with the runGadget function here.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:37.000
When you call runGadget, by default, it's going to create a gadget that appears in the RStudio viewer pane.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:42.000
But you could set runGadget like I did in the getPassword box.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:45.000
You set the viewer argument of it to dialogViewer.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:50.000
That would make the gadget appear in the dialog box like we saw before.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:53.000
You could also alternatively set this to browserViewer.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:56.000
dialogViewer needs a title.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:59.000
Its box is going to pop up, so we need to give it a title to explain the box.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:02.000
But the other browser viewer doesn't need that.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:05.000
I resource this.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:07.000
GetPassword.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:12.000
Now it's opening my browser, and here I have the gadget in this experience.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:18.000
Then if I wanted that in the viewer box, I would leave that in the paneViewer.

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:22.000
Or I'd leave viewer blank because this is the default.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:24.000
Resource that.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:25.000
GetPassword.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:28.000
Here I have it over in the paneViewer.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:32.000
So these three viewer functions are how you control where the gadget pops up.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:41.000
This is actually in the slides, so if you need a refresher on those, you're back here.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:43.000
You can see where I meant to cover this, but I forgot.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:47.000
Alright, so those are gadgets.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:52.000
What you use your gadgets to do and how you combine these pieces to shape the user experiences

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:55.000
is really up to you, your experience, and your imagination.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:00.000
But once you've created a gadget, there is something a little further you can go,

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:04.000
a place you can go further with the gadget that might be interesting,

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:06.000
so I wanted to cover it here in this webinar.

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:09.000
And what I'm talking about is something that we're calling RStudio Add-ins.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:17.000
And the idea here is with your gadget, you let your user leave the programming workflow temporarily

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:19.000
by calling a function here, GetPassword.

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:25.000
But you can make that even more seamless by giving them a GUI way to access your gadget.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:31.000
Instead of calling the function, they can actually access the gadget from the Add-ins menu

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:33.000
that is already in RStudio.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:39.000
So if you have a recent version of RStudio, definitely version 1 or higher,

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:41.000
you will have this Add-ins box up here.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:46.000
What appears in the drop-down menu next to Add-ins will depend a little about what packages you have

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:50.000
and whatnot, but this is a place that collects Add-ins.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:56.000
Add-ins are essentially shiny gadgets that have been built into the UI of RStudio IDE.

00:27:56.000 --> 00:28:00.000
So you can see I already have GetPassword listed here as an Add-in,

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:04.000
and if I were to click on that, it would open up this GetPassword box,

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:08.000
and then if I type in my password and click Done, that will get returned,

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:13.000
in this case, to the command line because of the way this Add-in is written.

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:18.000
If I wanted to, if this is something I find myself doing a lot,

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:21.000
I could go to Browse Add-ins and then Keyboard Shortcuts,

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:25.000
and actually set up a keyboard shortcut so I don't even have to click the Add-ins drop-down menu

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:30.000
to use this Add-in, and use the keyboard shortcut and so on.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:36.000
So these are just ways to make it even easier to access shiny gadgets when you're using R.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:42.000
The way to make an Add-in involves a package.

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:44.000
So Add-ins are shared through packages.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:48.000
You create your shiny gadget, which you recall is going to be an R function.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:55.000
You save that R function in a package, and then you register that function as a gadget

00:28:55.000 --> 00:29:00.000
by creating a file in this folder in RStudio Add-ins.dcf.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:04.000
This is a folder in your package, and for each Add-in you want to create,

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:08.000
you fill out these three fields, Name, Description, Binding, Interactive.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:14.000
And then whenever a user installs that package, this Add-in will be added to their list of Add-ins.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:18.000
So let's take a look at how that can work.

