So now I've created a package.

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:26.000
This literally is package everything you need for packages here.

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:31.000
If I want to build it into a package that I could install,

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:35.000
I'll go to build source package in the build menu here.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:39.000
We do have a webinar about making packages in RStudio, by the way,

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:40.000
so you can learn all this.

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:41.000
This just built a package.

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:46.000
It saved it as foo0.1.0.tar.gz on my desktop.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:49.000
Now if I want to install it in my RStudio session,

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:50.000
go to install.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:53.000
Instead of installing from CRAN, I'll install from a file.

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:56.000
Now I just need to find that file, which is right here.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:57.000
I just made it.

00:32:57.000 --> 00:32:58.000
All right.

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:02.000
So it's installing that package.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:04.000
It's not a very well-documented package, but it's there.

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:08.000
And now get password2 is in my add-ins list.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:09.000
Okay.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:13.000
So with that, that's, you know, we created this add-in in like 10 minutes.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:14.000
That's how easy it is to create an add-in.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:17.000
And anyone who gets this package, should I put it on CRAN or wherever,

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:24.000
they can instantly have access to those add-ins just by installing the package.

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:25.000
All right.

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:27.000
If you want some ideas about building add-ins,

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:29.000
there's two packages that contain add-ins.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:31.000
One's called add-in examples.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:33.000
That's on GitHub in the RStudio account.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:35.000
But if you Google for it, you'll find it.

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.000
One's called hadladdin.

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:39.000
Those are some add-ins that Hadley Wickham created.

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:42.000
That's on GitHub in his GitHub account.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:44.000
But if you Google hadladdin, you can find it.

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:46.000
And then there's a package called rstudio-api.

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:48.000
This doesn't contain add-ins,

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:50.000
but if you want to get in the business of creating add-ins,

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:52.000
this is a package you'll probably want to know about

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:57.000
because it provides R functions that allow you to control the RStudio IDE.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:34:02.000
So you could, for example, open a file or change the text inside of a file

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:05.000
using functions in RStudio API.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:09.000
When you combine that with an add-in, that could be a very useful thing to do.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:10.000
All right.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:13.000
So to conclude, to make a shiny gadget,

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:16.000
just remember you need to save it as a function,

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:20.000
use package-mini-ui to create the user interface,

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:23.000
and then use stop-app along with an observe-event statement

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:27.000
to return values back to whatever function called your gadget.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:29.000
So thank you for paying attention.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:31.000
And then the material that I present today

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:34.000
is encapsulated in three articles on various RStudio websites.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:36.000
I put them all right here.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:37.000
The first talks about gadgets.

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:39.000
The second talks about mini-ui.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:42.000
And the last one talks about creating RStudio add-ins.

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:45.000
In addition to these resources, we'll put these slides

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:49.000
and recording of the webinar up on our website within 48 hours.

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:53.000
So at this point, I will take some questions.

00:34:57.000 --> 00:34:59.000
Pop up a question here.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:02.000
So the first question is,

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:05.000
can you please describe how gadgets will work with RStudio Connect?

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:08.000
I'm assuming it will be identical to the way they work with Shiny.

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:12.000
Well, gadgets are invoked from your code.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:15.000
So a gadget's not going to appear unless,

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:18.000
first, someone runs a function or some code runs a function

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:20.000
that invokes the gadget,

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:23.000
or second, someone goes into the add-in menu

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:27.000
and opens an add-in because you've packaged the gadget as an add-in.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:32.000
So if you're using RStudio Connect to run code,

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:35.000
then you can expect your gadgets to be invoked as the code's run.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:39.000
But I can't really visualize at the moment how that process would work.

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:44.000
RStudio Connect's more designed for communicating things

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:46.000
that are already deployed.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:48.000
So that's very much the first Shiny app user case.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:51.000
You deploy the app so you don't really have to manage it.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:54.000
It takes care of itself at the moment someone visits it.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:57.000
With RStudio Connect, that moment will be curated

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:00.000
by RStudio Connect sending them the app at a certain time

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:03.000
or updating the app and sending it to someone else.

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:09.000
So I don't know if that made things more clear,

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:13.000
but that's how I think that will work out.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:16.000
Yeah, I've transferred a gadget and app several times.

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:17.000
Easy to do.

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:19.000
Well, every gadget, the way I think about it,

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.000
every Shiny gadget is an app.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:23.000
Not every Shiny app is a gadget.

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:27.000
And when you're using functions like stopApp to control your gadget,

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:29.000
it becomes very clear that your gadget is an app.

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:32.000
So I hope that I was never incorrect,

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:35.000
even though I might have been imprecise by transposing gadget and app.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:37.000
I apologize about that, Bernard.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:41.000
What happens if you use runApp at the bottom instead of runGadget?

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:43.000
Do you get a Shiny app instead?

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:46.000
That's a good question.

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:48.000
I think, especially on educations,

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:51.000
you will experience behavior that you want to steer clear of.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:56.000
runGadget gives you the freedom to open your Shiny app

00:36:56.000 --> 00:36:59.000
as a dialog box or in the pane or the browser,

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:01.000
which obviously runApp does as well.

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:04.000
But if you're using gadgets, stick with runGadget.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:06.000
There's a reason you create a separate function

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:08.000
and you shouldn't try to mix the two.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:10.000
Hi, I'm new to R.

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:13.000
Is the Shiny app gadget only applicable when we use RStudio only

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:15.000
or is it part of R language features?

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:20.000
Both Shiny and Shiny gadgets are IDE agnostic.

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:21.000
They're part of R.

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:25.000
You can create them with R without using RStudio IDE

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:27.000
and you can give them to people to use

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:30.000
even if those people are not using RStudio IDE.

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:34.000
Since we make RStudio IDE and we also make Shiny,

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:37.000
we've been able to really integrate them well with RStudio.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:41.000
Our hope is that RStudio makes it easier for you to create these things,

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:43.000
but you do not need to use RStudio.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:45.000
They're completely disconnected.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:53.000
How easy fast is it to convert a gadget into a Shiny app if needed?

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:54.000
It's very simple.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:56.000
Just unwrap it.

00:37:56.000 --> 00:37:59.000
Take the UI and server that you create in your function body

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:01.000
and define them outside the function body.

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:05.000
If you're relying on parameters of the function to supply things,

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:09.000
make sure that your UI and server can stand on their own

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:12.000
and then just replace runGadget with runApp.

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:15.000
What's inside that function is essentially a Shiny app,

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:18.000
so it's very easy to take it, move it outside the function

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:20.000
and have your Shiny app.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:21.000
Also, it's very easy to do the opposite,

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:24.000
to take an existing app and repackage it as a gadget.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:27.000
The things you'll want to look out for, though,

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:30.000
is how the layout looks when you go back and forth.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:35.000
By the way, any Shiny app can use the miniUI functions within the app

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:37.000
if you think that they're better for your particular app.

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:39.000
MiniUI works for all Shiny apps.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:44.000
Can you comment on a comparison of a Shiny gadget and a Shiny module?

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:45.000
That's a good question,

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:49.000
because they both are extensions of Shiny in a way.

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:52.000
A Shiny gadget is a complete Shiny app.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:55.000
A Shiny module is not a complete Shiny app.

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:58.000
It's a part of a Shiny app that's composable.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:01.000
So if you find yourself doing the same thing many times across apps

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:03.000
or even within an app,

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:06.000
a Shiny module would be a way to write all that code once

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:09.000
and then reuse it in multiple places.

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:12.000
It's sort of like the function equivalent for Shiny apps.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:15.000
In R, if you're running the same code multiple times,

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:18.000
you'd save it as a function and call that function multiple times.

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:21.000
In Shiny, if you're doing the same thing multiple times,

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:24.000
you'd save it as a module and call that module.

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:28.000
But modules are not designed to be a self-contained Shiny app on their own.

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:32.000
You always have to call them from within the context of a larger Shiny app

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:35.000
that finishes the packaging of that app.

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:37.000
That's not true with Shiny gadgets.

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:39.000
Shiny gadgets do exist on their own.

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:40.000
They're self-contained.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:44.000
So the two ideas are actually sort of orthogonal to each other.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:46.000
We have a webinar on Shiny modules

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:48.000
if you'd like to learn more about Shiny modules.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:52.000
Can gadgets be included in Shiny apps?

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:55.000
I think this kind of goes back to the Shiny modules idea.

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:57.000
A gadget is an app of its own.

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:58.000
It's a self-contained app.

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:01.000
So you wouldn't put it inside of another app.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:05.000
Whereas a Shiny module is Shiny code and functionality

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:09.000
that is designed to be called from a parent app,

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:10.000
a larger app of some sort.

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:13.000
So no, I wouldn't put a gadget inside a Shiny app.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:17.000
But here's a variation of that question

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:21.000
that might have some more insight, provide some more insight.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:24.000
Can you use gadgets within deployed Shiny apps?

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:32.000
You can have your Shiny apps call functions.

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:35.000
And functions that are called can call gadgets.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:36.000
So you can certainly try it out.

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:37.000
I haven't tried that out.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:40.000
And I don't know what you should expect should you do that.

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:45.000
I suspect that your Shiny app's deployed by a server

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:47.000
that's running R in the backend.

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:50.000
And if you have a trigger code that launches a gadget,

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:53.000
I wouldn't be surprised if that gadget's launched on the server

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:55.000
in its local R session so your user never sees it.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:58.000
But again, I'm just guessing here.

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:00.000
I have never tried that out myself.

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:02.000
I don't think that's really a use case we have.

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:08.000
Each gadget has its own surface design or what?

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:11.000
Will you create the UI that you want your gadget to have

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:13.000
using those mini UI components?

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:16.000
Whatever you store to that UI object

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:18.000
will determine what the gadget looks like.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:20.000
So that's the surface design.

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:23.000
Can you comment on the benefits and drawbacks

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:26.000
of Brush app compared to digraphs?

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:28.000
I'm not very familiar with digraphs.

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:30.000
So no, I don't think I can.

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:33.000
But if that is a package that someone developed

00:41:33.000 --> 00:41:34.000
to do something specific,

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:36.000
it's probably better than this Brush app,

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:38.000
which really is a trivial app that we just designed

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:41.000
to show off the different features of gadgets.

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:44.000
And one more question,

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:46.000
and then I'll turn it back over to Bill.

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:47.000
The question is,

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:49.000
I'm building a supply chain simulation

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:50.000
with object-oriented R.

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:52.000
Would it be possible to use gadgets

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:54.000
to provide a user interface for setting parameters

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:57.000
and controlling several plots, et cetera?

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:00.000
So this question is a bit specific,

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:04.000
but this sounds like the use case for a shiny app.

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:06.000
Gadgets are only for people

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:08.000
who are already in an R session

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:10.000
and writing code at the command line.

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:14.000
Shiny apps give you the chance

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:17.000
to curate your user's experience.

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:19.000
So they don't have to interact with R at all.

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:22.000
And you can certainly provide a portal to your simulation

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:23.000
using a shiny app.

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:24.000
That's what it's meant to do.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:26.000
So I'd recommend just using a shiny app for that.

